title: Add flatbuffers as a submodule.
body:
### Description
Adding flatbuffers as a submodule, to avoid using incompatible versions installed on the system.

### Motivation and Context
onnxruntime supports flatbuffers v1.12.0, but many systems include different versions. Additionally, Arch Linux [packages flatbuffers as a shared library](https://github.com/archlinux/svntogit-community/blob/packages/flatbuffers/trunk/PKGBUILD#L36), which adds a target `flatbuffers::flatbuffers_shared`, which in turn is not what [onnxruntime expects](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/cmake/onnxruntime_graph.cmake#L89). This causes builds to fail on Arch Linux.

This PR adds flatbuffers v1.12 as a submodule and builds it simultaneously with onnxruntime itself.

Fixes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/14981

title: Fix symbolic shape inference script on precision loss issue
body:
### Description
When calculating symbolic shape like `mul(get_int_val(values=[1024, 0.5]))`,
the current script calls `get_int_val()` to get values, which values becomes `[1024, 0]`.
Thus, the result of `mul(values)`->`mul([1024,0])`=0, but the expected shape size is 512

Fix: for math binary operations like `mul()` and `div()`, 
don't convert input shapes into integers if any possible precision loss happen;
keep the input shape as float, finish the operation, and cast final result into integer and output the shape.

Test cases are added:
1. mul(1024, 0.5)=>512 (before this fix, the output would be 0, as float 0.5 would be converted to int 0)
2. div(768, 1.5)=>512 (before this fix, the output would be 768, as float 1.5 would be converted to int 0)

### Describe the issue

I am trying to use the CUDA optimizations for the Stable Diffusion UNet described [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/main/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/models/stable_diffusion). I found that most optimizations work, though it does not fuse attention - `model.get_fused_operator_statistics()` always returns:

```
Optimized operators:{'Attention': 0, 'MultiHeadAttention': 0, 'LayerNormalization': 16, 'SkipLayerNormalization': 32, 'BiasSplitGelu': 16, 'GroupNorm': 61, 'NhwcConv': 98, 'BiasAdd': 0}
```

It appears the fusion script cannot find the QKV nodes ([here in `fusion_attention_unet.py`](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/750747d8c9f1a96bda182b9a8810f3f6a75d6bdc/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/fusion_attention_unet.py#L369-L376)).

The code I used to convert the UNet is [here](https://github.com/pykeio/diffusers/blob/9b0fe38e166747c6cc1a6ce5a9ee5f731a089170/scripts/sd2pyke.py#L168-L232).

I modified the original optimization script to only convert the UNet:

```py
import os.path

# _optimizer is copied from onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers at d834ec895af8c2dd6e718c21b575697c01b8ec4f

from optimizer import optimize_by_onnxruntime, optimize_model

in_path = Path('./model')

fusion_options = FusionOptions('unet')
fusion_options.use_multi_head_attention = True

m = optimize_model(
	str(in_path / 'unet.onnx'),
	model_type='unet',
	num_heads=0,

	use_gpu=True

m.get_fused_operator_statistics()
```

body:
I noticed that on `node_modules/onnxruntime-node/bin/napi-v3/darwin/arm64` there are pre-built binary files that are apparently targeting ARM64 mac. I don't have access to a mac device, so I can't verify if they any effect on Apple ARM64 devices (like those based on Apple Silicon).

Based on information on the `npm` website, these files have been bundled for more than year now, as far back as version `1.10`, which was published on December 2021:

![Screenshot_1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8589488/227755707-35dd49fd-3088-43eb-8e09-5c945ccf8f70.png)

Yet, there is no mention whatsoever of macOS ARM64 support of `onnxruntime-node`. Not on [https://onnxruntime.ai/](https://onnxruntime.ai/):

![Screenshot_2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8589488/227755759-f8638039-7a89-4017-b5d4-87e522f1cedb.png)

and not on [https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/main/js/node](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/main/js/node):

![Screenshot_3](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8589488/227755805-34c99639-5b68-45e6-b3b4-31b07f22e062.png)


There are also no related discussions or issues that I could find, including any requests or questions about supporting ARM64 macs, or anything related, which is odd.

I'm publishing a tool that is heavily based on `onnxruntime-node`, so I want to ensure that newer macOS devices (M1, M2) are supported directly. I can't test it so I don't know what exactly do these files are destined for.

title: Introduce register-efficient warp-wise Softmax
body:
improve softmax forward when number of elem to do softmax is between (1024,2048]

several optimizations done in the PR:
1. originally ort will call softmax_block_forward when shape is 1500, this will cause 5.53ms, however ort has another implementation called softmax_warp_forward, this function will only need 4.74ms, so i modified the function selection logic to call the faster version.
2. softmax_warp_forward will use register to cache the input in fp32 mode, this will consume many registers when data number is large and will make warp occupancy quite low, also compiler can do some of its optimizations, so the pr implements another version of softmax_warp_forward, it will use shared memory instead of register to cache the input; also when the for loop in the function has many iterations, actually disable loop unrolling will make kernel faster further.

the perf table between softmax_warp_forward1(the original version) and softmax_warp_forward2
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43435212/228491963-cf87e3b3-e69e-454c-bab6-7e62a25bf76b.png)


in open-ai whisper case, the kernel gain will be 5.53ms/3.03ms = 82% (softmax_block_forward vs softmax_warp_forward2)
